Notes

Displacement vector vs Velocity vector

  • What do they have in common:
    - Indicate something happening space
    - Both vectors
    Definition 2 (Velocity).

    Basically speed. How fast you're moving a car. You got Lamborghini cruising on the road at an unknown speed because we forgot the speedometer.

Definition 2 (Displacement).

Displacement is a vector quantity. The result should be a vector.
The MAGNITUDE of displacement, is a scalar. See diagram above

Example ((II) A projectile is fired with an initial speed of 36.6 ms at an angle of 42.2° above the horizontal on a long flat firing range. Determine (a) the maximum height reached by the projectile, (b) the total time in the air, (c) the total horizontal distance covered (that is, the range), and (d) the speed of the projectile 1.50 s after firing.).
This was taken from the textbook Physics: Principles with Applications by Douglas, Problem 20 Pg 69
Example (An athlete performing a long jump leaves the ground at a 27.0° angle and lands 7.80 m away. (a) What was the takeoff speed? (b) If this speed were increased by just 5.0%, how much longer would the jump be?).
This was taken from the textbook Physics: Principles with Applications by Douglas, Problem 28 Pg 69
Example ((II) A shot-putter throws the “shot” (mass = 7.3 kg) with an initial speed of 14.4 ms at a 34.0° angle to the horizontal. Calculate the horizontal distance traveled by the shot if it leaves the athlete’s hand at a height of 2.10 m above the ground).

This was taken from the textbook Physics: Principles with Applications by Douglas, Problem 20 Pg 69
